## 3. ActivityWatch

### Overview
- **Market Position:** Open-source, privacy-first automatic tracker
- **Users:** 50K+ (developers, privacy advocates)
- **Pricing:** Free (open-source)

### Strengths
- ✅ **100% local-first:** All data stored on device
- ✅ **Privacy absolute:** No cloud, no telemetry
- ✅ **Cross-platform:** Windows, macOS, Linux, Android
- ✅ **Open-source:** Auditable, extensible
- ✅ **Automatic tracking:** Window titles, browser URLs, AFK detection
- ✅ **Browser extensions:** Chrome, Firefox (track active tab)
- ✅ **Editor plugins:** VS Code, Sublime Text (WakaTime-style)

### Weaknesses
- ❌ **Raw data visualization:** Charts are basic, not actionable
- ❌ **No manual entry:** Can't add time retroactively
- ❌ **No reporting:** No weekly summaries, no invoicing
- ❌ **No focus metrics:** Just time logged, no productivity score
- ❌ **Developer UX:** Requires technical setup

### Why it Matters
ActivityWatch proves **local-first time tracking is viable**. Users love the privacy model but hate the lack of polish.

**Neuman Brain Opportunity:** Combine ActivityWatch privacy + Toggl UX = killer product.

